{% title "Symmetric matrix definition" %}
{% description "A matrix A is symmetric if it is equal to its transpose, i.e.,  $A=A^T$." %}

<p>A matrix $A$ is symmetric if it is equal to its {% intlink matrix_transpose %}transpose{%endintlink%}, i.e.,  $A=A^T$.  A matrix $A$ is symmetric if and only if swapping indices doesn't change its components, i.e., $a_{ij} = a_{ji}$.<p>

<p>The matrix
\begin{gather*}
  A=\left[
  \begin{array}{cccc}
  1 & 2 & 3 & 4\\
  2 & 5 & 6 & 7\\
  3 & 6 & 8 & 9\\
  4 & 7 & 9 & 10
  \end{array}
  ]
\end{gather*}
is symmetric while the matrix
\begin{gather*}
  B=\left[
  \begin{array}{cccc}
  1 & 2 & 3 & 4\\
  12 & 5 & 6 & 7\\
  3 & 6 & 8 & 9\\
  4 & 7 & 9 & 10
  \end{array}
  ]
\end{gather*}
is not symmetric as $2=a_{12} \ne a_{21}=12$.</p>

